    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-12-05T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-12-05T00:00:00-05:00" n="490"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d490">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">Hopkins Papers</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">President <persName corresp="#p_RFD1" type="from"
                            >Roosevelt</persName> to Prime Minister <persName corresp="#p_CC2"
                            type="to">Churchill</persName>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d490fn1">A facsimile of this document is printed in
                            <persName corresp="#p_SRE1">Sherwood</persName>, <ref target="#pg_801"
                            >p. 801</ref>, where the first line of the text begins, as typewritten,
                        “The President proposes to send over his signature”, and handwritten changes
                        (by <persName corresp="#p_HHL1">Hopkins</persName>, according to <persName
                            corresp="#p_SRE1">Sherwood</persName>) make the text read as printed
                        here.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Cairo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-12-05">December 5,
                            1943</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rend="flushleft">
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Memorandum for: the Prime Minister</hi>
                </p>
                <p>I propose to send over my signature the following message to the <gloss
                        target="#t_Generalissimo1">Generalissimo</gloss> tonight. Do you concur in
                    this action?<note n="2" xml:id="d490fn2">The paper is endorsed at the bottom by
                            <persName corresp="#p_CRFES1">Churchill</persName>: “I agree. WSC 5
                        XII”.</note>
                </p>
                <quote rend="blockquote">
                    <p>“Conference with <persName corresp="#p_SIV1">Stalin</persName> involves us in
                        combined grand operations on European continent in late spring giving fair
                        prospect of terminating war with Germany by end of summer of 1944. These
                        operations impose so large a requirement of heavy landing craft as to make
                        it impracticable to devote a sufficient number to the amphibious operation
                        in Bay of Bengal simultaneously with launching of <gloss target="#t_Tarzan1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tarzan</hi>
                        </gloss> to insure success of operation.</p>
                    <p>“This being the case: Would you be prepared go ahead with <gloss
                            target="#t_Tarzan1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tarzan</hi>
                        </gloss> as now planned, including commitment to maintain naval control of
                        Bay of Bengal coupled with naval carrier and commando amphibious raiding
                        operations simultaneous with launching of <gloss target="#t_Tarzan1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tarzan</hi>
                        </gloss>? Also there is the prospect of <gloss target="#t_B291">B–29</gloss>
                        bombing of railroad and port Bangkok.</p>
                    <p>“If not, would you prefer to have <gloss target="#t_Tarzan1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tarzan</hi>
                        </gloss> delayed until November to include heavy amphibious operation.
                        Meanwhile concentrating all air transport on carrying supplies over the hump
                        to air and ground forces in China.</p>
                    <pb facs="0908" n="804" xml:id="pg_804"/>
                    <p>“I am influenced in this matter by the tremendous advantage to be received by
                        China and the Pacific through the early termination of the war with
                            Germany.[”]<note n="3" xml:id="d490fn3">The telegram to <persName
                                corresp="#p_CKS1">Chiang</persName> was sent from Cairo at 11:05
                            p.m., December 5, 1943, Cairo time. It was sent to Washington and
                            relayed to Chungking via military channels. On December 7, 1943,
                                <persName corresp="#p_SJW1">Stilwell</persName> (at Cairo) cabled
                                <persName corresp="#p_HTG1">Hearn</persName> (at Chungking) that
                                <persName corresp="#p_HTG1">Hearn</persName> should see <persName
                                corresp="#p_CKS1">Chiang</persName> and urge him to proceed with
                            China’s part in the campaign despite the cancellation of <gloss
                                target="#t_Buccaneer1">
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Buccaneer</hi>
                            </gloss>; see <hi rend="italic">
                                <persName corresp="#p_SJW1">Stilwell</persName>’s Command
                                Problems</hi>, p. 74. <persName corresp="#p_CKS1"
                            >Chiang</persName>’s reply to <persName corresp="#p_RFD1"
                                >Roosevelt</persName> is printed in the same publication, p.
                            74.</note>
                    </p>
                </quote>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_RFD1">F[<hi rend="smallcaps">ranklin</hi>] D[<hi
                                rend="smallcaps">elano</hi>] R[<hi rend="smallcaps"
                            >oosevelt</hi>]</persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
